<br>
1. Disturb the spawning proccess creating a small year class of bass.<br>
<br>
2. Catching and killing the vulnerable large spawning fish reducing the trophy population of a lake.<br>
<br>
With the exception of a few special cases (there are always exceptions, right?) I believe point number one is virtually never an issue. There are always plenty of nests that never get discovered by fishermen. And the fact that all the california lakes get hammered during the spawn with no apparent harm is good evidence to me as well.<br>
<br>
Number two is a problem that I'm concerned about, but it's less of a spawning issue than it is a catch-and-release issue. I would strongly support C&amp;R only regulations during the spawn on many of our lakes. It just breaks your heart to watch 10-15 pound bass being caught on nightcrawlers by weekend warrior trout fishermen who just throw it in the freezer.<br>
<br>
Overall this issue is a lot like the C&amp;R arguments... more emotion than facts. I don't even know if my concerns of problem #2 are biologically supported.<br>
<br>
And finally. I can't wait for the spawn! I'm going to bed fish as much as I possibly can this year. One of my goals for the year is to catch a 10+ from a bed. But I will always catch-photo-and-release these fish at the location of the nest and release it immediately.<br>
<br>
Any way you look at it, sight fishing is some of the most fun and exciting ways to catch a bass.<br>
<br>
Nico<br>
